05828nam a22008535i 9780812295054DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20182018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122950547 a10.9783/97808122950542doi  a(DE-B1597)497593  a(OCoLC)1036302666  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ535b.L36 2018 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a306.8109732231 aLefkovitz, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStrange Bedfellows :bMarriage in the Age of Women's Liberation /cAlison Lefkovitz. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b8 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics and Culture in Modern America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Problem of Marriage in the Age of Women’s Liberation -- tChapter 2. The End of Breadwinning and Homemaking -- tChapter 3. Blaming Feminism for the Fragile Family -- tChapter 4. Race, Welfare, and Marriage Regulation -- tChapter 5. Sham Marriages, Real Love, and Immigration Reform -- tChapter 6. Gay Marriage and “Homosexual Households” -- tConclusion. The End of Marriage as We Know It -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the inaugural issue of Ms. Magazine, the feminist activist Judy Syfers proclaimed that she "would like a wife," offering a wry critique of the state of marriage in modern America. After all, she observed, a wife could provide Syfers with free childcare and housecleaning services as well as wages from a job. Outside the pages of Ms., divorced men's rights activist Charles Metz opened his own manifesto on marriage reform with a triumphant recognition that "noise is swelling from hundreds of thousands of divorced male victims." In the 1960s and 70s, a broad array of Americans identified marriage as a problem, and according to Alison Lefkovitz, the subsequent changes to marriage law at the state and federal levels constituted a social and legal revolution.The law had long imposed breadwinner and homemaker roles on husbands and wives respectively. In the 1960s, state legislatures heeded the calls of divorced men and feminist activists, but their reforms, such as no-fault divorce, generally benefitted husbands more than wives. Meanwhile, radical feminists, welfare rights activists, gay liberationists, and immigrant spouses fought for a much broader agenda, such as the extension of gender-neutral financial obligations to all families or the separation of benefits from family relationships entirely. But a host of conservatives stymied this broader revolution. Therefore, even the modest victories that feminists won eluded less prosperous Americans—marriage rights were available to those who could afford them.Examining the effects of law and politics on the intimate space of the home, Strange Bedfellows recounts how the marriage revolution at once instituted formal legal equality while also creating new forms of political and economic inequality that historians—like most Americans—have yet to fully understand.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aDomestic relationszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMarriage lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMarriagezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryxPublic opinion. 0aMarriagezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLaw.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DG